'''Noah Arinzechukwu Okafor''' {{Audio|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Chikeme Chizurum-Noah Arinzechukwu Okafor.wav|Listen|help=no}}(born 24 May 2000) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|LeedsUni}} club [[Leeds United]] and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]].

==Club career==
===Basel===
Okafor played his first youth football with local team FC Arisdorf. In 2009 he moved to the youth of [[FC Basel|Basel]] and continued through all the stages of their youth academy. He advanced to their first team during their [[2018–19 FC Basel season|2018–19 season]] and on 31 January 2018, Okafor signed his first professional contract with his club under head coach [[Raphaël Wicky]].<ref name="fcb-aktuell-2018/19-Okafor">{{cite web | date = 31 January 2018 | url = https://www.fcb.ch/aktuell/news/1-mannschaft/2018/01/der-fcb-verlaengert-mit-noah-okafor-bis-2020 | title = Der FCB verlängert mit Noah Okafor bis 2020 |website=FC Basel 1893 | language = de | access-date = 2022-11-16}}</ref> He played his debut for their first team on 19 May 2018 in the home game against [[FC Luzern]]. The trainer substituted him in for the injured [[Mohamed Elyounoussi]] in the 34th minute and the game ended in a 2–2 draw.<ref name="fcb-achiv-2018/19-FCB-FCL">{{cite web | date = 19 May 2018 | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=31250 | title = FC Basel – FC Luzern 2:2 (1:1) |website= Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv" | access-date = 2022-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club in the second round of the 2018–19 season on 28 July 2018 in the 1–1 away draw against [[Neuchâtel Xamax FCS|Xamax]].<ref name="fcb-aktuell-2018/19-Xamax-FCB">{{cite web | date = 28 July 2018 | url = https://www.fcb.ch/aktuell/news/1-mannschaft/2018/07/kein-sieger-zwischen-xamax-und-basel | title = Kein Sieger zwischen Xamax und Basel |website=FC Basel 1893 | language = de | access-date = 2022-11-16}}</ref>

Under trainer [[Marcel Koller]] Basel won the [[2018–19 Swiss Cup|Swiss Cup in the 2018–19 season]]. In the first round Basel beat FC Montlingen 3–0, in the second round [[FC Echallens|Echallens Région]] 7–2 and in the round of 16 [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]] 1–0. In the quarter-finals [[FC Sion|Sion]] were defeated 4–2 after extra time and in the semi-finals [[FC Zürich|Zürich]] were defeated 3–1. All these games were played away from home. The final was held on 19 May 2019 in the [[Stade de Suisse|Stade de Suisse Wankdorf Bern]] against [[FC Thun|Thun]]. Striker [[Albian Ajeti]] scored the first goal, [[Fabian Frei]] the second for Basel, then [[Dejan Sorgić]] netted a goal for Thun, but the result was 2–1 for Basel.<ref name="fcb-achiv-fcb-thun-cupfinal-2018–19">{{cite web | last = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv" | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=31396 | title = FC Basel – FC Thun 2:1 (1:0) | format = | publisher = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv" | access-date = 2022-11-16}}</ref> Okafor played in four cup games and scored a goal in the semi-final against Zürich.

Between the years 2017 and 2020 Okafor played a total of 72 games for Basel scoring a total of nine goals. 39 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League]], seven in the [[Swiss Cup]], eight in the [[UEFA]] competitions (Champions League and Europa League) and 18 were friendly games. He scored three goals in the domestic league, two in the cup, two in the European competitions and the other two were scored during the test games.<ref name="fcb-achiv-Noah Okafor">{{cite web | last = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv" | year = 2020 | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=9788 | title = Noah Okafor – FCB statistic | format = | publisher = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv" | access-date = 2022-11-16}}</ref>

===Red Bull Salzburg===
[[File:Meistertellerübergabe Saison 2021-22 (2022-05-21) 30.jpg|thumb|Okafor in 2022]]
On 31 January 2020, Okafor signed for [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Red Bull Salzburg – Welcome to Salzburg Noah Okafor |url=https://www.redbullsalzburg.at/en/fc-red-bull-salzburg/news/saison_2019_20/welcome-to-salzburg-noah-okafor.html |website=redbulls |access-date=26 February 2020 |language=de}}</ref>

On 8 December 2021, Okafor scored the only goal of the game as Salzburg defeated [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the final group stage match of the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]. The win meant Salzburg secured progression to the Round of 16 and became the first-ever Austrian club to qualify for the knockout stages of the Champions League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2032708--salzburg-vs-sevilla/|title=Salzburg-Sevilla|website=UEFA|date=8 December 2021|access-date=8 December 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/okafor-strike-sees-salzburg-historic-win-over-sevilla-2021-12-08/|title=Okafor strike sees Salzburg to historic win over Sevilla|website=Reuters|date=8 December 2021|access-date=8 December 2021}}</ref>

On 7 September 2022, during a [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group stage]] match against [[AC Milan]], Okafor scored a remarkable goal, leading the match to a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |last=UEFA.com |title=Salzburg-Milan: UEFA Champions League 2022/23 Group stage |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2035650--salzburg-vs-milan/ |access-date=2023-07-21 |website=[[UEFA]] |language=en}}</ref> After outmaneuvering Milan's defender [[Pierre Kalulu]] and goalkeeper [[Mike Maignan]] with a 'gurkerl' trick shot, his goal landed in the bottom right corner of the net, sparking widespread celebrations in the stadium.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |date=2022-09-06 |title=Milan held to 1–1 draw at Salzburg in Champions League opener |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/lifestyle/sports/milan-held-to-1-1-draw-salzburg-champions-league-opener-2022-09-06/ |access-date=2023-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-06 |title=AC Milan come from behind to earn draw in Salzburg as Italians get off to slow start in Champions League |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/champions-league/2022-2023/red-bull-salzburg-v-ac-milan-follow-live_sto9126321/story.shtml |access-date=2023-07-21 |website=Eurosport |language=en}}</ref>

===AC Milan===
On 22 July 2023, Okafor signed for Italian [[Serie A]] side [[AC Milan]] until 30 June 2028.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-07-22 |title=OFFICIAL STATEMENT: NOAH OKAFOR |url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/media/2023-07-22/official-statement-noah-okafor |access-date=2023-07-22 |website= |publisher=[[AC Milan]] |language=en}}</ref> Okafor made his Serie A debut for AC Milan on 21 August 2023 against [[Bologna FC 1909|Bologna]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 August 2023 |title=Bologna 0–2 AC Milan (Aug 21, 2023) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/679225 |access-date=2023-10-01 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> On 27 September 2023, Okafor scored his first goal for the Rossoneri in a 3–1 away victory against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 September 2023 |title=Cagliari 1–3 AC Milan, Serie A TIM 2023/2024: the match report |url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/serie-a/2023-09-27/comfortable-win-over-cagliari |access-date=2023-10-01 |website=AC Milan |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=27 September 2023 |title=Cagliari 1–3 AC Milan – Serie A result as Ruben Loftus-Cheek, Fikayo Tomori and Noah Okafor earn the Rossoneri a comeback win in Sardinia |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2023-2024/live-cagliari-ac-milan_mtc1450559/live-commentary.shtml |access-date=2023-10-01 |website=Eurosport |language=en}}</ref> Three days later, he scored the second goal against [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] in 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pulisic scores as AC Milan beat Lazio to keep pace with Inter |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/679285 |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> His third goal of the season came on 17 December against [[AC Monza|Monza]], when he scored his team's third goal in a comfortable 3–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=AC MILAN 3–0 MONZA: HOSTS CLAIM EASY WIN TO KEEP INTERNAZIONALE AND JUVENTUS IN SIGHTS IN SERIE A |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2022-2023/ac-milan-v-monza-serie-a-live_sto9921497/story.shtml |website=EuroSport |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> On 20 January 2024, he came off the bench to score a stoppage-time winner against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], it was the first win for AC Milan in the former's stadium since 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Udinese 2–3 AC MILAN: ALLEGED RACIST ABUSE OF MIKE MAIGNAN MARS DRAMATIC COMEBACK WIN FOR ROSSONERI |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2022-2023/udinese-v-ac-milan-serie-a-live_sto9975718/story.shtml |website=EuroSport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Oliver |title=A milestone up for the grabs: all key stats ahead of Udinese vs. Milan |url=https://sempremilan.com/all-key-stats-udinese-ac-milan-2024 |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref>

On 17 August 2024, Okafor netted his first goal of the [[2024–25 Serie A|2024–25 season]] in the opening match, which ended in a 2–2 draw against [[Torino FC|Torino]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/serie-a/2024-08-17/late-comeback-to-secure-a-point |title=Late comeback earns a point |publisher=AC Milan |date=17 August 2024 }}</ref> In January 2025, his loan move to [[Bundesliga]] club [[RB Leipzig]] was canceled after he failed a medical examination due to a muscular injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/leihe-geplatzt-okafor-wechselt-nicht-nach-leipzig-1081878/artikel |title=Leihe geplatzt: Okafor wechselt nicht nach Leipzig |publisher=Kicker |language=de |date=14 January 2025 }}</ref>

====Loan to Napoli====
On 3 February 2025, Okafor joined Serie A club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] on loan until the end of the 2024–25 season, with an option of a permanent transfer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sscnapoli.it/en/ufficiale-okafor-e-un-nuovo-calciatore-del-napoli/ |title=Okafor completes Napoli move |publisher=SSC Napoli |date=3 February 2025 }}</ref> On May 23, 2025, Okafor won his first trophy in Italy, the fourth Scudetto in Napoli's history.<ref>{{cite web |last=Young |first=Peter |url=https://football-italia.net/official-napoli-serie-a-champions-for-2024-25/ |title=Official: Napoli crowned Serie A Champions for 2024–25 |publisher=Football Italia |date=23 May 2025 }}</ref> His presence in the squad was thought to be unnecessary as he only featured in four matches under coach [[Antonio Conte]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Fisher |first=Oliver |url=https://sempremilan.com/napoli-not-convinced-okafor-investment-milan |title=TMW: Okafor currently set for Milan return – Napoli not convinced of €23.5m investment |publisher=Sempre Milan |date=21 March 2025 }}</ref>

===Leeds United===
It was reported on 19 August 2025 that agreement had been reached for Okafor to sign for [[Premier League]] club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/article/leeds-united-reach-agreement-ac-101000274.html |title=Leeds United reach agreement with AC Milan to sign Noah Okafor in €21m deal| publisher=Yahoo Sports |date=19 August 2025}}</ref> On 21 August 2025, Okafor officially moved to England and joined the club on a four-year contract in a deal reported to be £18,000,000.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-08-21 |title=Leeds United sign forward Noah Okafor from AC Milan to break Premier League spending record |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce83w74gl54o |access-date=2025-08-21 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 20 September 2025, scoring Leeds' third goal in a 3–1 away win at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Leeds United come back to beat beleaguered Wolverhampton Wanderers |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c3e75z98q2yt |access-date=2025-10-08 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 13 April 2026, he netted his first brace for Leeds United in a 2–1 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]], securing his club's first away league victory over [[Leeds United F.C.–Manchester United F.C. rivalry|their rivals]] since 1981.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stone |first=Simon |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c2lwv150jwwt |title=Manchester United 1–2 Leeds United |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 April 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
Okafor played various international games for the [[Switzerland national under-15 football team|Swiss U-15]] and [[Switzerland national under-17 football team|U-17 teams]]. He played his first game for the [[Switzerland national under-18 football team|U-18 team]] on 9 May 2018 in the 1–1 draw against the [[Italy national under-18 football team|Italy U-18 team]].

Okafor made his debut for the [[Switzerland national football team|senior national team]] debut on 9 June 2019 in the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 UEFA Nations League third place game]] against England, as an 113th-minute substitute for [[Haris Seferovic]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UEFA]]|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/match/2024421--switzerland-vs-england/|title=Switzerland v England game report|date=9 June 2019}}</ref> He scored his first international goal for Switzerland on 15 November 2021, in their World Cup qualifying game against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], a win which secured automatic qualification for Switzerland to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/noah-okafor-sends-switzerland-into-world-cup-heaven-34082736|title=Noah Okafor sends Switzerland into World Cup heaven|website=One Football|date=15 November 2021|access-date=24 November 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/world-cup-qualification-uefa/2022/switzerland-v-bulgaria-follow-live-world-cup-qualifying_sto8629288/story.shtml|title=Switzerland beat Bulgaria to snatch group c top spot from Italy to qualify automatically for World Cup|website=Eurosport|date=15 November 2021|access-date=24 November 2021}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Born in [[Binningen, Switzerland]], Okafor is the son of a Nigerian father and a Swiss mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allnigeriasoccer.com/read_news.php?nid=25068|title=Basel's Nigerian Midfielder Noah Okafor Notches Two Assists vs CSKA :: All Nigeria Soccer – The Complete Nigerian Football Portal|website=www.allnigeriasoccer.com}}</ref> His younger brothers Elijah and [[Isaiah Okafor|Isaiah]] are also footballers, playing respectively for [[FC Lugano|FC Lugano II]] and the Under 21 of [[FC Zürich]].

